        <title>Dimensions and Features of Academic Language</title>
        <contents>&lt;table border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="5" style="border: 1px solid #19568b;"&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;th scope="col" style="background-color: #19568b;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium; color: #ffffff;"&gt;Dimensions&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th scope="col" style="background-color: #19568b;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium; color: #ffffff;"&gt;Features&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/th&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Message&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Text type and register&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Clarity and coherence&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Organization and structure (visuals, paragraphs_&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Transitions between ideas&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Sentences&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Sentence structure (compound/complex; embedded clauses) and length&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Complex verb tenses and passive voice&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Dense noun phrases&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Words and phrases&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Cross-disciplinary terms&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Figurative expressions and multiple meanings&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Content vocabulary&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Affixes and tools&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Adapted from Zwiers, O'Hara, and Pritchard (2014). To hear Jeff Zwiers describe this framework, view this short video as well:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;object width="100%" height="183"&gt;&lt;param name="movie" value="//www.youtube.com/embed/PfN1vxXR6oU?hl=en_US&amp;amp;version=3&amp;amp;rel=0" /&gt;&lt;param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /&gt;&lt;param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /&gt;&lt;embed width="100%" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/v/PfN1vxXR6oU?hl=en_US&amp;amp;version=3&amp;amp;rel=0" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" title="Adobe Flash Player" /&gt;&lt;/object&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Listen to audio:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@@PLUGINFILE@@/ELL_MOD1_UNIT2_0100.mp3"&gt;ELL_MOD1_UNIT2_0100.mp3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;details&gt;&lt;summary&gt;Audio transcript&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Much of the research and many of the models for exploring academic language have come from work in K–12 education because ELL children need academic language to keep up with their mainstream peers. As educators of adult ELLs, it is important to think of academic language as professional language as well. Zwiers, O’Hara, and Pritchard (2014) provided a helpful framework for analyzing this academic and professional language. Any time you see the word text, that can mean written or oral text, for example a lecture or a presentation. What type of text is it (e.g., a compare-contrast essay, a categorization of ideas, a description of a process)? What are the features of the message, or discourse? What are the sentence-level features in the text? How complex is the grammar? What words and phrases make a text more or less academic? Let’s apply this framework to a text on personality and the birth-order theory that you might use in an intermediate to advanced adult ELA class.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
