        <title>Unpacking the Academic Language of a Text</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Now let's analyze the academic language in a reading text: &lt;a href="@@PLUGINFILE@@/M1U2_S27_48_Theory_508.pdf" title="Birth-order theory"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Personality and the Birth-Order Theory&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Let's first consider the text type, audience, and purpose:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type&lt;/strong&gt;: Nonfiction, informational text that could appear in a basic textbook or a magazine&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Audience&lt;/strong&gt;: Students of psychology; general public interested in learning about the theory&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Purpose&lt;/strong&gt;: To educate or inform non-experts&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Now we will use the dimensions of academic language adapted from Zwiers et al. (2014) to analyze this text.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
