        <title>Examples of Academic Language: Message Level</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;How are the ideas in the text organized? How does the layout support the organization of the text?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Introductory paragraph signals categories (&lt;em&gt;within each group&lt;/em&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Clear paragraph headings (visual clue)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;What grammar structures help to structure the ideas in the text?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Sequence markers: &lt;em&gt;first-born children, middle children&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Use of simple present when describing tendency&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Listen to audio:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@@PLUGINFILE@@/ELL_MOD1_UNIT2_0110.mp3"&gt;ELL_MOD1_UNIT2_0110.mp3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;details&gt;&lt;summary&gt;Audio transcript&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We can look at a reading text with these dimensions in mind. We start with the message level and see what can help an adult ::ELL understand the overall organization of a text. We can point these features out to learners, for example, tell them to notice bold headings and signal words such as first or second. Look at the sentence- and word-level language issues that may pose challenges for learners.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
