        <title>Examples of Academic Language: Sentence Level</title>
        <contents>&lt;table border="0" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="5" align="right" style="background-color: #fff2b5; ; width: 20%;"&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Example: &lt;strong&gt;A very dense noun phrase!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Birth-order theory is (&lt;strong&gt;a sociological and psychological concept that describes the tendency for people born into a particular birth order in a family (oldest, youngest, middle, or only child) to have certain personality traits.)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;h2 style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Different types of sentence structures&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;For those interested in learning more about helping learners unpack these noun phrases, see &lt;a target="_blank" title="What’s in a Noun Phrase? Judging the Difficulty of a Reading Text by Understanding the Complexity of Noun Phrases" href="http://minnetesoljournal.org/spring-2014/whats-in-a-noun-phrase-judging-the-difficulty-of-a-reading-text-by-understanding-the-complexity-of-noun-phrases"&gt;Swierzbin (2014)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Different types of sentence structures (compound/complex; embedded clauses)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul style="text-align: left;"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;It is believed that because parents treat children in each birth order differently, children develop distinctively different personalities.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Complex verb tenses and passive voice&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul style="text-align: left;"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;They &lt;em&gt;may have had&lt;/em&gt; an older sister.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;It &lt;em&gt;is believed&lt;/em&gt; that...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;It &lt;em&gt;is found&lt;/em&gt; that...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Dense noun phrases&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul style="text-align: left;"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;A noun phrase can be the subject or the object of a sentence (and either one of those can contain multiple phrases).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;Listen to audio:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;a href="@@PLUGINFILE@@/ELL_MOD1_UNIT2_0120.mp3"&gt;ELL_MOD1_UNIT2_0120.mp3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;details&gt;&lt;summary&gt;Audio transcript&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Noun phrases can be extremely complex, including embedded phrases and clauses. In the sentence at the right, everything in italics is the object of the sentence! If you are interested in ideas on how to break down long noun phrases in a systematic way, and one that learners can use with other readings, see What’s in a Noun Phrase? by Bonnie Swierzbin (2014).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
